 approaching, and no matter how that sucker got there, it's high time to get rid of it!  But how??<br>
Well, The secret to ridding yourself of Gamer's gut is to reduce the amount of fat in your body.  Ok, sounds easy enough....  but we've all tried, and if you still have yours then we can assume the attempt wasnt successful :P<br>
<br>
But dont lose hope! there's a way to get rid of it.  The trick is knowing how to Burn Fat.<br>
<br>
Fat has about 9 calories per gram, and it's an awesome source of energy. Your body can make all the fat it needs, in fact, there's little fat that a person does need to injest on their own, accept for a few fatty acids found in some plants (yes plants have fatty acids :P)<br>
<br>
So enough about all that, how shall we Burn the Fat.  Well it's easy, But first you have to know something about the metabolic Process.  (simplified version <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
There are 3 ways your body creates energy, 2 are anaerobic (without oxygen) and one is areobic(with oxygen)  The first way is by burning Sugar or glucose.  This metabolic reaction creates energy, and leaves one byproduct, Lactic Acid.  When the amount of Lactic acid in your muscles is too high, pain develops, and a &quot;stiff&quot; feeling sets in.  Once this reaction (sugar burning) stops, the muscles can slowly break down the lactic acid.  So this reaction isnt really that bad, but it cant be sutained for long periods of time.<br>
<br>
The second way is by burning Protein and Water.  This metabolic reaction is very negative for the body.  First off, Protein is only stored in living tissue.  Any other protein consumed is Stripped of it's Nitrogen and turned into sugar.  So unless you just had a quarter pounder with cheese, your body stripes it's muscles and cells for the protein required for this reaction.  This reaction also dehydrates your body.  IF this reaction is prolonged then the nitrogen balance in the body can be upset, causing a lot of negative affects (dizzyness, cramps, and body odor)  This metabolic Reaction creates energy, and leaves another by product, Uric Acid.  This acid is toxic to the body and must be removed when levels get to high. however this acid cannot leave the body with a certain amount of water.  Since this metabolic reaction uses up water, it usually leaves the body without enough water to rid itself of the by product it creates. This situation increases the time the acid remains in the body, thus prolonging it's negative affects. (this metabolic reaction is not recommended as healthy way to create energy.) <br>
<br>
The Third way is by burning Oxygen, Carbohydrates, and Fat.  This metabolic reaction is a very efficient way for the body to create energy.  However, it does require a few things.  It requires you to Breathe.  It requires you to eat enough fruits and veggies to maintain a nature glucose level. (breads and grain also have sugar, infact almost all plants use glucose as their source of energy) Starch is another form of a complex carbohydrate.  This reaction also requires Fat (hey if you've got a gamer's gut! no problem there!)  Also, it requires all the necessary vitamins and minerals (in their proper, respective amounts) in order for this metabolic reaction to occur.  This metabolic reaction creates energy, and it's only byproduct is heat.  <br>
<br>
The breathing aspect of this third metabolic reaction is often over looked, to breathe efficiently, the adomen must move in snyc' with the diaphram.  When inhaling, It curves downward(pushing at the stomach and intensines).  When exhaling, it then Curves upward, forcing the air out of the lungs and through the nose/mouth.  This allows for the stomach and intensines to return to a more comfy position.  But often when we have a Gamer's Gut, were always sucking it in to impress the ladies, there by cutting our oxygen supply. If your body doesnt have enough oxygen to stay in the third metabolic reaction, then it will switch to one of the other 2 metabolic reactions.  So the only way to get rid of the Gamer's gut... Is to Poke it out! and breathe.  (if that fine girl didnt stop while you were sucking it in, it couldnt hurt to show that puppy off... who knows maybe she'll go for that sort of thing.  Either way you'll be trimming it down the whole while :P)  <br>
<br>
So dont waste another minute, whip that gut into shape, and strut down the coastline in style.<br>
The beaches are waiting :P<br>
<br>
Mozenwrath<br>
p.s.<br>
<br>
Your gamers gut will not go away in a few days, or even a week! This sort of thing takes time.. And it is equal to the amount of energy you use on a daily basis. i.e. the more you do, the faster it goes. Eat a healthy (raw, boil or bake your food. eat fresh meats and produce, reduce fried, fat laddened foods) and move your body(ie use energy, otherwise your body stores it.) :P Rest when you need to rest.  Sleep when you need to sleep. i garantee by June/mid july that gamers gut will be just a memory.(just keep in mind you'll &quot;feel&quot; the difference before you see it.) If you feel pain durning your exercise, evaluate your technique.  There should be little to no joint pain, and the only pain that should be there is in the muscles(and very shortly)  Exercise isnt suppose to be painful, it's suppose to the fun, so keep it that way <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Increasing your intake of coldwater fish AND their oil, (i.e. tuna in spring water) is excellent for joint pain during or after exercise. The high density cholestorol is what helps your joints, So drink the juice too. Also, fish of any kind are a good source of high quality protein, that's low in fat.(just dont fry it)<br>
<br>
equation for carbohydrate + Fat + oxygen burn.<br>
<br>
 carbohydrates supply 25% of calories in the reaction, Fat supply the other 75%. Oxygen is there to help create the chemical reaction.  3500 calories are in one pound of fat.  So 3500 X .25 = amount of carb calories needed to burn that much fat(or one pound).  Look at this sort of thing as a process, a journey. It isnt something you want to try to do all in one day (or a week, or a month for that matter) Take it one day at a time. Also, as you lose fat by exercise, you gain muscle mass. so your weight may be in a state of flux. but it's more healthy when you have more muscle mass than fat(you still need some fat [10 to 20 % of body weight] though), it isnt so much what the scale says, but What Muscle/Fat ratio your weight represents. <br>
